<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-simultaneous-linear-and-quadratic-equations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Simultaneous Linear and Quadratic Equations</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.1 Quadratic Expressions and Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Solve simultaneous equations involving linear and quadratic equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Introduce Learners to equations involving linear and quadratic expressions. Understand that when a quadratic and linear expression are equated, there are usually two solutions (except for repeated roots).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Help students with algebraic manipulation if they are struggling. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The pattern Learners should recognise in (e) is that the solutions are 1 and 2 (for the left blue line), 3 (for the red line), and 4 and 5 (for the right blue line), forming the pattern 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                When Learners are creating their own connected expressions, encourage them to use variables to get the properties they look for, not just guess and check. E.g. they could call the quadratic <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Inspired by Foster, 2013: https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/0020739X.2013.770089-->
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Consider the following triangle of <q>connected expressions</q>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-connected-expressions">
                <caption>Connected Expressions: <m>x^2 - x + 10</m>, <m>2x+8</m>, and <m>8x-10</m></caption>
                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[
                            box/.style={
                                draw,
                                rectangle,
                                inner sep=5pt,
                                align=center
                            },
                            every node/.style={font=\large}
                        ]

                        % One parameter controls the overall size
                        \def\R{3}

                        % Geometric vertices of an equilateral triangle
                        \coordinate (T) at (90:\R);
                        \coordinate (L) at (210:\R);
                        \coordinate (R) at (330:\R);

                        % Outer triangle
                        \draw[blue!40, thick] (L) -- (T) -- (R);
                        \draw[red!40, thick] (L) -- (R);

                        % Boxes centered at the triangle vertices
                        \node[box, fill=blue!20] (top)   at (T) {$x^2 - x + 10$};
                        \node[box, fill=red!20] (left)  at (L) {$2x + 8$};
                        \node[box, fill=red!20] (right) at (R) {$8x - 10$};

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <p>
                Each line of the diagram joins the two expressions in an equation; the red line at the bottom represents the equation <m>2x + 8 = 8x - 10</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do:</alert>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        How many solutions do you expect for the red line? (How many values of <m>x</m> will solve <m>2x + 8 = 8x - 10</m>?)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Check your guess by finding the solution(s) for <m>x</m> on the red line. Write your answer(s) in the middle of the line.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What about for the blue lines? (How many values of <m>x</m> will solve <m>x^2 - x + 10 = 2x + 8</m>, or <m>x^2 - x + 10 = 8x - 10</m>?)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Check your guess by finding the solution(s) for both blue lines. (If there are two solutions, you can write them on opposites sides of the line.) Was your guess correct?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Do you see a pattern in the solutions?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Try and create your own connected expressions! Can you get all the solutions to be integers? Just even numbers? Just prime numbers? What about making 4 connected expressions! What happens if you connect two quadratic equations?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Share your work with your fellow learners.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>

        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

