    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Simultaneous means we are looking for value(s) of x that make both expressions equal at the same time.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A linear expression looks like <m>mx + c</m>, where <m>m</m> and <m>c</m> are constants, and the highest power of <m>x</m> is 1. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A quadratic expression looks like <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>, where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are constants, and the highest power of <m>x</m> is 2.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        When a linear and quadratic expression are equated, there are usually two solutions (except for repeated roots).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The pattern in the solutions of the connected expressions is that they are consecutive integers. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Changing the coefficients of the linear and quadratic expressions affects the number and nature of the solutions. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>To solve a simultaneous equation where one is linear and one is quadratic:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Set the two expressions equal to each other.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Rearrange the equation to set it to zero.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Factorise the resulting quadratic equation or use the quadratic formula to find the solutions for <m>x</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight> 

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the simultaneous equations: <m>y = x + 2</m> and <m>y = x^2 - 4</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Setting the equations equal to each other:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x + 2 = x^2 - 4</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rearranging to set to zero:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x^2 - x - 6 = 0</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Factorising:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>(x - 3)(x + 2) = 0</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, <m>x = 3</m> or <m>x = -2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the simultaneous equations: <m>y = 2x + 1</m> and <m>y = x^2 - 3x + 2</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>2x + 1 = x^2 - 3x + 2</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x^2 - 5x + 1 = 0</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using the quadratic formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x = \frac{5 \pm \sqrt{25 - 4}}{2} = \frac{5 \pm \sqrt{21}}{2}</m>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the simultaneous equations: <m>y = -x + 4</m> and <m>y = x^2 - 2x + 1</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>-x + 4 = x^2 - 2x + 1</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rearranging to set to zero:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x^2 - x - 3 = 0</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Factorising:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>(x - 3)(x + 1) = 0</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, <m>x = 3</m> or <m>x = -1</m>.
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example> 
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                 Find the intersection of <m>y = x + 7</m> and <m>y = x^2 - 4x + 5</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Equate the two equations to find the points of intersection:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x + 7 = x^2 - 4x + 5</m>
            </p>
            <p>
               Move terms to one side:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x^2 - 5x - 2 = 0</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Solve for <m>x</m> using the quadratic formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x = \frac{5 \pm \sqrt{25 + 8}}{2} = \frac{5 \pm \sqrt{33}}{2}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find <m>y</m> by substituting <m>x</m> into the linear equation (<m>y = x + 7</m>):
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>y = 12.37</m> or <m>y = 6.63</m>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>

